To further specify the best candidates for the bullet land grooves, we rely on the heuristic that most of the middle 50\% of the bullet will be occupied by striae. Therefore, we can eliminate any strong lines detected within this region. An example of the middle fifty percent of a bullet land can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:middle-fifty} where the middle fifty percent of the bullet land is bordered by green colored vertical lines. We note that the grooves are well away from this middle fifty percent region, making this a suitable heuristic. We then select the highest normalized score of the lines detected outside of the middle fifty percent of the bullet land. We claim then that this is our detected bullet groove. If on the off chance that the strongest feature detected is within the middle 50\% area of the bullet land, then the grooves are set to be the borders of the middle 50\% area. 

Once features are chosen to describe both the left and right hand grooves of the bullet land the \textbf{get\_grooves\_hough} function translates these features into two equations for lines, where the left-hand and right-hand groove are denoted $\gamma_{lh}, \gamma_{rh}$, respectively. It is worthwhile to note at this point that our calculations have been in terms of pixels detected in an image rather than the microns of the bullet scan. So we must transform our equations of lines from being in terms of pixels to microns. This is accomplished inside the \textbf{get\_grooves\_hough} function by the helper function \textbf{pix\_to\_micron} which subtracts one from the pixel location (since pixels start indexed at one and microns start indexed at zero), then multiplies that pixel location by the resolution of the x3p-scan($r_s$). In addition, we can also introduce manually identified adjusts into our groove equations. Each test set tends to have an optimal adjust value that provides a more accurate groove identification by shifting the automatically identified grooves into the interior of the bullet land by the number of microns specified by the adjust on both the left and right-hand sides of the bullet land. Because we are interested in the slope with respect to the y-direction we calculate our linear equations as follows, where $y_i$ is any y-location on the bullet land and $\alpha$ is the groove adjust:

\begin{center}
  $\gamma_{lh} = (x_b -1)*r_s + m_y*y_{i} + \alpha$ \\
  $\gamma_{rh} = (x_b -1)*r_s + m_y*y_{i} - \alpha$
\end{center}

 Unlike other methods available in the \textit{GrooveFinder} package, the \textbf{get\_grooves\_hough} function does not provide a groove estimate at an optimized crosscut. The output of the  \textbf{get\_grooves\_hough} function are a set of two functions that correspond to the left and right-hand grooves. So to produce an actual estimate of our groove location we need to input a y-location into our two functions. For a single point-estimate we can input the y-location of a single crosscut using the \textbf{x3p\_optimize\_crosscut} function from the \textit{bulletxtrctr} package. However to visualize our groove estimates across the entire bullet land we have created a helper function called \textbf{get\_mask\_hough} that creates a colored mask over our bullet land of our groove estimates as shown in Figure \ref{fig:get-mask-hough-example}. 
 
