\section{Conclusion}

Overall, the Hough method appears to offer a slight improvement in groove location identification than the Rollapply method presented by \cite{hare2017}. Interestingly enough, the effectiveness of the Hough method varies with the side of the groove being identified. As demonstrated in both the Phoenix PD Set and the Hamby Set 44, it seems as if the identifications for both the Hough and Rollapply method are more accurate on the right hand side of the bullet land. It is worth noting however, that the method we use to evaluate the accuracy of groove identifications (AOM scores) contains a slight bias towards the Rollapply method. The reason for this is that the manual groove identifications were made as adjustments to existing Rollapply groove estimates. So reasonably accurate Rollapply estimates of groove locations were accepted without adjustment as a proper identification while less accurate Rollapply estimates were adjusted accordingly. Regardless, the appeal of the Hough method lies in its relative simplicity as an application of a simple computer vision algorithm and its ability to draw information from the entirety of a bullet scan. Further examination of the precision of some of the heuristics used to define this process would be good candidates for further examination. 

